124
00:08:25,919 --> 00:08:26,969
它是一个框架体系。
It's a framework.

125
00:08:26,969 --> 00:08:28,763
它不是一栋单一的建筑。
It's not a single building.

126
00:08:28,763 --> 00:08:34,184
所以它内部不会有一根贯穿170公里的单一核心筒。
So it doesn't have one single core that stretches for 170 km inside it.

127
00:08:34,184 --> 00:08:40,765
相反，它由数以千计的核心筒组成，每一个都像普通楼宇一样单独建造。
Instead, it's made up of thousands of cores, each built individually just like any other core.

128
00:08:40,765 --> 00:08:44,238
但关键在于，这些核心筒支撑着你看到的黄色甲板，
But crucially, these support the yellow decks you can see here,

129
00:08:44,238 --> 00:08:47,380
也就是整个结构的主层（primary decks）。
which are going to be the primary decks of the structure.

130
00:08:47,461 --> 00:08:50,346
这些主层就像城市的主干道、主要大道，
They're like the kind of the main streets, the main avenues,

131
00:08:50,346 --> 00:08:52,654
而核心筒则是横向的街道。
and the cores are going to be the cross streets.

132
00:08:52,654 --> 00:08:58,320
就像曼哈顿的街道网格，只不过想象它被折叠起来，垂直叠放。
It's just like the Manhattan grid except imagine it folded up and stacked vertically.

133
00:08:58,320 --> 00:09:02,553
城市的真正活力，将在这个框架之内迸发。
It's here within this framework where the city is going to really come to life.

134
00:09:02,553 --> 00:09:09,943
学校、医院、住宅、交通基础设施，一切让城市运转的要素都将在此汇聚。
You'll find schools, hospitals, homes, transport infrastructure, everything you need to make a city function.

135
00:09:09,944 --> 00:09:12,496
这正是目前正在建造的内容。
This is what's currently under construction.

136
00:09:12,496 --> 00:09:15,019
两排500米高的塔楼。
Two rows of 500 meter towers.

137
00:09:15,019 --> 00:09:19,655
一期工程将吊装480万吨钢外伸臂梁（steel outrigger beams），
Phase one will see 4.8 8 million tons of steel outrigger beams hoisted up

138
00:09:19,655 --> 00:09:22,640
以支撑贯穿其间的五层主层结构。
to support the five decks running through each.

139
00:09:22,640 --> 00:09:27,468
在普通摩天大楼建设中，钢结构和外墙装饰会在这一阶段之前就开始安装。
Usually on skyscrapers, the steel work and cladding will start to be added before you get to this stage.

140
00:09:27,468 --> 00:09:30,264
它们基本上是跟着核心筒一路向上推进，
They basically follow the core up the building,

141
00:09:30,264 --> 00:09:32,168
这也是2026年令人期待的原因——
which is why 2026 is so exciting

142
00:09:32,167 --> 00:09:35,022
届时建设应当真正成形，
because things should really start to take shape

143
00:09:35,023 --> 00:09:37,759
进度也会明显加快。
and we should start to see some fast progress.

144
00:09:43,120 --> 00:09:47,990
这就是那个数十亿……抱歉，我是说数万亿美元的问题。
That is the billiondoll sorry I mean trillion dollar question.

145
00:09:47,990 --> 00:09:50,669
先从混凝土说起。
Let's start by talking about concrete.

146
00:09:50,669 --> 00:09:54,480
大规模浇筑混凝土极为复杂。
Now pouring concrete at scale is incredibly complex.

147
00:09:54,480 --> 00:09:56,884
浇筑太慢，混凝土会凝固不均。
Pour it too slowly and it'll set unevenly.

148
00:09:56,884 --> 00:10:00,117
但浇筑太快，原材料可能会离析分层。
But pour it too fast and the ingredients can split.

149
00:10:00,117 --> 00:10:03,255
配比过湿，混凝土会变脆。
Get the mixture too wet and your concrete's going to be brittle.

150
00:10:03,255 --> 00:10:05,971
太干，则会变得像瑞士奶酪一样千疮百孔。
Too dry and it'll end up like Swiss cheese.

151
00:10:05,971 --> 00:10:10,768
说到底，这需要长时间保持绝对的一致性。
Basically, it relies on total consistency for long periods of time.

152
00:10:10,768 --> 00:10:16,702
目前已经浇筑了数百万吨混凝土，这是相当扎实的施工记录。
Now, millions of tons of concrete have already been poured, which is a pretty solid track record.

153
00:10:16,702 --> 00:10:20,627
但那是在海岸附近，可以方便地获取供应。
But that's here on the coast with access to supply lines.

154
00:10:20,627 --> 00:10:26,479
这座城市还有漫长的路要走，要深入广袤的腹地，
This city still has a very long way to go up into a vast hintterland

155
00:10:26,479 --> 00:10:34,224
那里既没有本地建材，也极度缺乏一种关键原料——水。
with no access to local materials and a near total lack of one very key ingredient, water.

156
00:10:34,224 --> 00:10:35,859
但有一个方案。
But there's a plan.

157
00:10:35,860 --> 00:10:39,965
一切从OXAGON开始，这是NEOM的另一个大型项目，
It all begins here at the Oxigon, another of NEM's mega projects

158
00:10:39,965 --> 00:10:45,096
一座大型海水淡化厂（desalination plant）将把数十亿升海水
where a massive desalination plant is going to pump billions of lers of seawater

159
00:10:45,095 --> 00:10:48,302
泵送至沿城市全线分布的蓄水库。
to reservoirs dotted along the length of the city.

160
00:10:48,302 --> 00:10:53,104
这些蓄水库将为一个耗资1.9亿美元的混凝土工厂网络提供水源，
They'll feed a 190 million US network of concrete factories

161
00:10:53,104 --> 00:10:57,662
每天可生产20,000立方米混凝土。
capable of producing 20,000 cub m of concrete every day.

162
00:10:57,662 --> 00:10:59,290
但问题来了。
But there's a catch.

163
00:10:59,290 --> 00:11:02,724
目前为止，这一切都尚不存在。
As it stands, none of this currently exists.

164
00:11:03,044 --> 00:11:06,067
OXAGON的建设直到2025年中才刚刚启动。
Work on oxygen only began in mid 2025.

165
00:11:06,067 --> 00:11:09,200
那些大型混凝土工厂距离落成还遥遥无期，
Those vast concrete plants are still a very long way off

166
00:11:09,200 --> 00:11:13,732
目前混凝土靠本地生产，用水则由油罐车运输，
and concrete's currently being produced locally with water shipped in by tankers,

167
00:11:13,733 --> 00:11:16,027
这绝非可扩展的解决方案。
which is by no means a scalable solution.

168
00:11:16,027 --> 00:11:23,171
事实上，近来又有未经证实的报道称，该海水淡化厂已被悄然搁置。
In fact, yet again, there have recently been unconfirmed reports that the desalination plant has been quietly scrapped.

169
00:11:23,171 --> 00:11:25,155
我在这里可不是在吹毛求疵。
I'm not just splitting hairs here.

170
00:11:25,155 --> 00:11:29,477
THE LINE在不到9年的时间内还有相当宏大的目标要实现。
The line has got some very ambitious targets to meet in less than 9 years time.

171
00:11:29,477 --> 00:11:34,773
NEOM体育场将悬挂在THE LINE内部350米的高空，
The Neome Stadium is set to be suspended 350 m up in the air inside the line

172
00:11:34,773 --> 00:11:38,396
并预定承办2034年FIFA世界杯的比赛。
and is set to host games at the 2034 FIFA World Cup.

173
00:11:38,396 --> 00:11:42,488
届时球迷们都会买票入场的。
Games that people are going to be buying tickets for.

174
00:11:42,488 --> 00:11:49,285
说实话，要让人相信这一点，我现在就希望看到更多可扩展推进的实质证据。
And to be honest, for that to be credible by this stage, I'd expect to see a lot more evidence of scalable activity.

175
00:11:49,285 --> 00:11:53,753
但在2025年底站在这里，眼前的一切
Instead, what it looks like as I stand here at the end of 2025

176
00:11:53,753 --> 00:11:57,788
更像是一个急于建点什么、任何东西都行，
is a project that's trying to build something, anything,

177
00:11:57,788 --> 00:12:01,679
只求积攒些势头、证明批评者错误的项目。
just to gain a bit of momentum and prove people wrong.

178
00:12:06,480 --> 00:12:08,720
那么，他们到底在建什么？
So, what are they actually building?

179
00:12:08,720 --> 00:12:11,451
我们一直提到的一期工程究竟是什么？
What is this phase one we keep mentioning?

180
00:12:11,451 --> 00:12:18,079
当你看到这片沙漠里的巨大沟壑时，你以为会建造什么？
Well, when you saw this and this massive trench in the desert, what did you think was going to be built?

181
00:12:18,079 --> 00:12:24,889
也许是全部，或者一半，至少四分之一吧。然而，都不是。
Maybe the whole thing or maybe half or at least a quarter. Well, no.

182
00:12:25,130 --> 00:12:31,418
尽管在沙漠中挖出了那条绵延170公里的巨型沟槽，
Despite building that enormous 170 km long cutting through the desert,

183
00:12:31,418 --> 00:12:37,796
实际上他们只是在建造这一期工程——仅仅是THE LINE中区区2.4公里的一段。
they're actually only building this phase 1, a mere 2.4 km of the line.

184
00:12:37,796 --> 00:12:43,355
别误会，这本身仍是一栋绝对庞大的建筑，
Now, don't get me wrong, it's still an absolutely musive building in its own right,

185
00:12:43,355 --> 00:12:48,379
但它不过占整条THE LINE结构的不到1.5%。
but it accounts for less than one and a half% of the entire line structure.

186
00:12:48,379 --> 00:12:52,033
你可能会觉得有点大失所望。我确实如此。
You might be feeling a little bit short changed by that. I know I certainly am.

187
00:12:52,034 --> 00:12:53,786
但这背后有一定的策略考量。
But there is a bit of strategy here.

188
00:12:53,786 --> 00:12:56,723
你看，NEOM团队正在利用一期工程
You see, the Neome team are using phase 1

189
00:12:56,723 --> 00:13:02,167
来建造城市中最具规模、最为壮观的一批锚点资产（anchor assets）。
to construct some of this city's biggest and most spectacular anchor assets.

190
00:13:02,889 --> 00:13:10,108
所谓锚点资产，就是一旦建成，便能吸引周边投资与发展的项目。
An anchor asset is something that once it is completed attracts investment and development around that area.

191
00:13:10,108 --> 00:13:13,329
一个绝佳的例子就是曼哈顿的高线公园（Highline），对吧？
A really great example would be the Highline in Manhattan, right?

192
00:13:13,329 --> 00:13:19,157
那本是一段废弃的高架铁轨，后来被改造成了一座公共公园。
It was this elevated sort of derelict abandoned rail tracks and it was revitalized and turned into a public park.

193
00:13:19,158 --> 00:13:26,960
正是由于那个项目，高线公园周边如今已成为曼哈顿最炙手可热、价格最高昂的地段之一。
And because of that project, now that area around the Highline has become one of the most expensive and coveted areas in Manhattan.

194
00:13:27,120 --> 00:13:30,473
>> 整个结构被划分为800米长的模块（modules）。
>> The whole structure is divided into 800 m long modules.

195
00:13:30,473 --> 00:13:34,695
把它们想象成THE LINE的街区或社区单元。
Think of these as being like the neighborhoods or city blocks of the line.

196
00:13:34,695 --> 00:13:39,016
一期工程将在场地西端建造其中三个模块，
Phase one is going to see three of these built near the western end of the site

197
00:13:39,016 --> 00:13:42,079
汇聚城市最为壮观的几大特色设施。
containing some of the city's most spectacular features.

198
00:13:42,079 --> 00:13:47,751
届时将建有一座可停靠世界最大邮轮的人工码头、
There's going to be a man-made marina capable of hosting the world's biggest cruise ships,

199
00:13:47,751 --> 00:13:49,831
46,000人容量的NEOM体育场，
the 46,000 capacity neon stadium,

200
00:13:49,831 --> 00:13:54,810
以及悬挂于入口处如同巨型枝形吊灯的迎宾构筑物。
and hanging below a vast chandelier welcoming people into this giant structure.

201
00:13:54,810 --> 00:13:58,246
NEOM在这里所做的，本质上是在说：
What Neon is trying to do here is basically say

202
00:13:58,246 --> 00:14:02,559
我们将出资建造一批锚点资产，
we're going to fund and build a collection of anchor assets

203
00:14:02,559 --> 00:14:07,530
下一阶段的发展将在此基础上有机展开。
around which sort of the the next phase will organically take place.

204
00:14:07,530 --> 00:14:10,800
这就是这里所宣称的目标。
That is the that is the that is the stated goal here.

205
00:14:10,800 --> 00:14:13,187
>> 从很多角度来看，这确实很有道理。
>> Now in many ways that makes a lot of sense.

206
00:14:13,187 --> 00:14:17,421
这是一套基于行业通行标准的成熟策略。
It's a sophisticated strategy based on industry-wide standards.

207
00:14:17,421 --> 00:14:24,880
问题在于，这是一座坐落在沙漠中、绵延170公里的城市。
Where it doesn't make sense is that this is a 170 km long city in the desert.

208
00:14:27,920 --> 00:14:30,630
THE LINE本应是一座彻底打破常规、
The line is supposed to be a revolutionary city

209
00:14:30,630 --> 00:14:34,204
以最大胆的方式颠覆我们对城市认知的
that tears up the rule book in the most audacious way possible

210
00:14:34,204 --> 00:14:37,317
革命性城市。
and changes the way we think about our cities forever.

211
00:14:37,317 --> 00:14:37,375
革命性城市。


212
00:14:37,375 --> 00:14:39,642
对于一个权力不受约束的雄心勃勃的领导人来说，
For an ambitious leader with unchecked power,

213
00:14:39,642 --> 00:14:43,672
这正是那种能够俘获全世界想象力的项目。
it's exactly the type of project you take on to capture the world's imagination.

214
00:14:43,672 --> 00:14:46,960
但对其他所有人来说，这是一场巨大的赌博。
But for everyone else, it's a huge risk.

215
00:14:47,120 --> 00:14:49,912
>> 我们常说，开发是一场里亚尔和哈拉拉的游戏，对吧？
>> We like to say that development is a dollars and cents game

216
00:14:49,912 --> 00:14:52,029
>> 我们常说，开发是一场里亚尔和哈拉拉的游戏，对吧？
or in this case a real and halahas game, right?

217
00:14:52,029 --> 00:14:54,959
你必须对成本保持近乎疯狂的专注。
You have to be so maniacally focused on cost.

218
00:14:54,959 --> 00:14:58,792
然而，在这里，这个项目既是一个建设工程，
However, here this development is part construction project

219
00:14:58,792 --> 00:15:02,950
也是沙特阿拉伯未来蓝图的某种象征，对吧？
and part sort of symbol for what Saudi Arabia can become, right?

220
00:15:03,111 --> 00:15:05,004
而这一切都可以追溯到最高层。
And it goes all the way to the top.

221
00:15:05,004 --> 00:15:09,200
王储MBS是每个人最终向其负责的那个人。
The crown prince MBS is the one that everyone ultimately answers to.

222
00:15:09,200 --> 00:15:12,120
问题就来了：他得到的是真实的信息吗？
So the question becomes, is he being told the truth?

223
00:15:12,120 --> 00:15:14,562
他得到的是他真正需要知道的内容吗？
Is he being told exactly what he needs to know?

224
00:15:14,562 --> 00:15:21,300
NEOM的领导层是否有足够的底气，对王储某些更为天马行空的设想说不？
Is there leadership strong enough on Neome to push back on, let's say, some of the Prince's more fantastical visions?

225
00:15:21,300 --> 00:15:25,264
因为他随时可能走进来说："哦，我实际上想让它朝这个方向弯，
Because he may go in and say, "Oh, I actually want this to curve this way,

226
00:15:25,264 --> 00:15:27,835
或者我想让它跨越这个东西。"
or I want this to kind of jump over this thing."

227
00:15:27,835 --> 00:15:32,621
他脑子里每一个这样的念头，都可能转化为数十亿美元的成本超支（cost overruns）
And each of those ideas in his head can turn into billions of dollars of cost overruns

228
00:15:32,621 --> 00:15:34,959
和数月乃至数年的工期延误，对吧？
and months or even years of delays, right?

229
00:15:34,959 --> 00:15:37,711
而这对大规模开发来说，根本行不通。
And that doesn't really work well for large scale development.

230
00:15:37,711 --> 00:15:43,840
THE LINE自宣布以来，就面临着围绕其所谓人道代价的激烈批评。
Ever since the line was announced, it's faced intense criticism around its alleged human cost.

231
00:15:43,920 --> 00:15:47,360
>> 住宅、学校、医院——从地图上抹去。
>> Homes, schools, hospitals wiped off the map.

232
00:15:47,360 --> 00:15:51,437
>> 有指控称工地上存在现代奴役行为，
>> There have been allegations of using modern-day slavery on sites

233
00:15:51,437 --> 00:15:55,027
以及对拒绝搬迁的部族成员下达处决令。
and orders to execute tribes people who refuse to relocate.

234
00:15:55,027 --> 00:15:59,679
这些指控遭到NEOM和沙特阿拉伯政府的强烈否认。
Allegations that Neom and the Saudi Arabian government vehemently deny.

235
00:15:59,679 --> 00:16:04,935
除此之外，我们和其他记者很难、甚至根本无法真正进入施工现场，
Beyond that, it's been very difficult slash impossible for us or any journalists

236
00:16:04,935 --> 00:16:07,103
当然，沙特阿拉伯对待媒体的方式
to gain real access to the sites,

237
00:16:07,104 --> 00:16:13,280
与其他地方本就截然不同。
though relationships with the press are of course approached very differently in Saudi Arabia.

238
00:16:14,320 --> 00:16:19,040
但这堵沉默之墙，给整个项目的根基蒙上了一层阴影。
But that wall of silence casts a shadow over the fundamentals of this project.

239
00:16:19,040 --> 00:16:23,478
为了这个视频，我们联系了数十位与THE LINE相关的人士，
We reached out to dozens of people involved in the line for this video,

240
00:16:23,478 --> 00:16:27,041
几乎没有人愿意出镜受访，都担心遭到报复。
and almost nobody would talk to us for fear of reprisals.

241
00:16:27,920 --> 00:16:32,651
残酷的现实是，当沙特阿拉伯致力于成为一个更加进步的社会，
The hard truth is that as Saudi Arabia works to become a more progressive society,

242
00:16:32,651 --> 00:16:36,516
努力在2030愿景框架下推动文化变革时，
as it works to change its culture as part of that vision 2030 plan,

243
00:16:36,516 --> 00:16:42,800
它必须学会处理好与境外自由媒体的关系。
it's going to have to learn to master its relationship with the free press beyond its borders.

244
00:16:43,120 --> 00:16:47,788
>> 质疑这个项目的人，在某种程度上都撞上了这堵文化的高墙。
>> People who are asking questions about this project are running into that clash of cultures in a way.

245
00:16:47,788 --> 00:16:53,839
你想搞清楚为什么成本翻了三倍，或者为什么某个方案被替换，或者为什么有些东西改变了，或者为什么
You want to understand why costs have tripled or why this has been replaced or why this has changed or why there's been no updates

246
00:16:53,839 --> 00:16:59,759
某某项目迟迟没有进展，但你面对的依然是一个向来不需要向任何人交代的地方。
on XYZ, but you're still dealing with a place that is used to not having to answer to anybody.

247
00:17:03,680 --> 00:17:09,437
如果THE LINE真的建成，它并不会是第一座从零开始建造的城市。
Now, if the line does get built, it won't be the first showpiece city constructed from scratch.

248
00:17:09,437 --> 00:17:10,682
这就是巴西利亚（Brasília）。
This is Brazilia.

249
00:17:10,682 --> 00:17:15,469
1960年建城，取代里约热内卢成为巴西的首都。
Founded in 1960, it replaced Rio de Janeiro as Brazil's capital.

250
00:17:15,469 --> 00:17:20,826
与THE LINE一样，它建在一个当时被视为偏远荒蛮的地方。
Just like the line, it was built in what was perceived as a remote and inhospitable location.

251
00:17:20,827 --> 00:17:25,996
更与THE LINE相似的是，这座城市的规划方案是前所未有的。
And even more like the line, the city's plan was like nothing anyone has seen before.

252
00:17:25,996 --> 00:17:28,887
它设计于20世纪50年代的喷气时代，
It was designed in the 1950s, the jet age,

253
00:17:28,887 --> 00:17:32,191
彼时航空技术飞速发展，
when rapid advances in aviation, and the jet set

254
00:17:32,192 --> 00:17:35,840
"喷气族"代表着一切前沿与未来。
represented all that was cutting edge and futuristic.

255
00:17:35,840 --> 00:17:40,200
巴西利亚，意在展示一个在现代重生的国家。
Brazilia was meant to represent a country reborn in the modern era.

256
00:17:40,200 --> 00:17:43,228
因此，它被设计成飞机的形状。
So, it was designed like an airplane.

257
00:17:43,228 --> 00:17:45,878
政府大楼坐落于机头，
Government buildings are housed in the cockpits

258
00:17:45,878 --> 00:17:47,795
住宅区沿机翼铺展，
with housing laid out on the wings

259
00:17:47,795 --> 00:17:49,825
军事区则位于机尾。
and a military district in the tail.

260
00:17:49,825 --> 00:17:54,800
机身形成一条宏伟的主轴，贯通全城。
The fuselage forms a monumental axis uniting the whole city.

261
00:17:55,440 --> 00:18:01,808
与巴西利亚一样，THE LINE某种程度上也是一个国家为自己塑造新时代前瞻性符号的尝试。
Just like Brazilia, the line is kind of an attempt to create a new forward-looking symbol for a nation.

262
00:18:01,808 --> 00:18:07,280
只不过，它的灵感不是来自蓝天，而是来自科幻小说的页面。
But rather than looking to the skies, it takes inspiration from the pages of science fiction.

263
00:18:08,160 --> 00:18:12,359
我突然收到一封来自一位沙特阿拉伯女性的邮件，
Out of the blue, I got an email from a Saudi Arabian woman

264
00:18:12,359 --> 00:18:18,079
邀请我就THE LINE的美学风格提供意见，
inviting me to talk with her about giving input into the aesthetics of the line

265
00:18:18,079 --> 00:18:22,640
她明确表示，王储对赛博朋克（cyberpunk）非常感兴趣。
and she made it clear that he was very interested in cyberpunk.

266
00:18:22,640 --> 00:18:29,300
>> 克里斯·哈布尔斯·格雷是一位学者和作家，撰写了大量关于赛博朋克及其他议题的著作。
>> Chris Hables Gray is an academic and author who's written extensively about cyberpunk and other topics.

267
00:18:29,300 --> 00:18:34,366
THE LINE本身似乎部分灵感来源于《雪崩》（Snow Crash）——
The line itself seems to be based in part on something from Snow Crash,

268
00:18:34,366 --> 00:18:39,574
一部小说，其中的虚拟现实世界
a novel where the virtual reality world was built around one long street,

269
00:18:39,574 --> 00:18:42,000
围绕一条无限延伸的虚拟长街而建。
an almost infinite virtual street.

270
00:18:42,320 --> 00:18:45,009
>> 即使你对这个词不熟悉，
>> Even if you're not familiar with the term,

271
00:18:45,009 --> 00:18:48,654
你也一定在各处见过赛博朋克的美学风格，
you're going to have seen the cyberpunk aesthetic everywhere,

272
00:18:48,654 --> 00:18:52,000
从电子游戏到电视剧，再到《银翼杀手》（Blade Runner）这样的电影。
from video games to TV shows and movies like Bladeunner.

273
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:58,800
克里斯是为THE LINE前身项目提供背景研究的少数几位人士之一，
Chris was one of a handful of people asked to provide background research for what we now know as the line

274
00:18:59,039 --> 00:19:05,925
>> 我收集了大量赛博朋克及相关科幻类型文学中的图片和引文，
>> and I collected a lot of images and quotes from cyberpunk and related types of science fiction writing

275
00:19:05,925 --> 00:19:08,351
我认为他们可能会觉得有用，
that I thought they might find useful

276
00:19:08,351 --> 00:19:15,679
我被告知要重点关注城市规划、赛博朋克的城市理念，以及相关的所谓"朋克"流派。
and so I was told to look especially at urban planning urban ideas of cyber punk but also the related so-called punk genres.

277
00:19:15,679 --> 00:19:18,992
我没能亲历，但有几位人士在场。
I didn't get to see this but several people were there.

278
00:19:18,992 --> 00:19:24,542
王储确实出席了一场定期举办的展示或展览，汇聚了大量这类理念，
The prince did arrive at a scheduled demonstration or exhibition of a lot of these ideas

279
00:19:24,542 --> 00:19:27,254
据说主要就是一些大幅图片。
which they said was mainly just big images.

280
00:19:27,254 --> 00:19:33,839
于是他挑选了自己喜欢的，据说这些内容后来被融入了整座城市的建设规划中。
So then he chose what he liked and uh these was theoretically incorporated into the plans for building the whole city.

281
00:19:35,200 --> 00:19:38,277
>> 这些是克里斯与NEOM分享的部分图片。
>> These are some of the images that Chris shared with Neome.

282
00:19:38,277 --> 00:19:44,400
看着它们，你能清晰地看到与THE LINE早期阶段发布的概念图之间的明显关联。
Looking at them, you can see the clear link with the concept images released in the early stages of the line.

283
00:19:51,039 --> 00:19:54,741
如果说THE LINE有哪一方面真的像是从电子游戏里走出来的，
If there's one aspect of the line that does seem straight out of a video game,

284
00:19:54,741 --> 00:19:56,355
那就是覆盖整个建筑外立面的
it's the distinctive mirror finish

285
00:19:56,354 --> 00:19:58,774
标志性镜面外观。
that covers every patch of the building's exterior.

286
00:19:58,775 --> 00:19:58,822
标志性镜面外观。


287
00:19:58,822 --> 00:20:03,471
镜面玻璃并不是什么新鲜事物，但它确实存在一些弊端。
Now, reflective glass isn't anything new, but it does come with some disadvantages.

288
00:20:03,471 --> 00:20:08,027
建筑上使用的这类玻璃，是通过一种被称为溅射镀膜（sputter coating）的工艺，
The type used on buildings is made by transferring metal deposits onto glass

289
00:20:08,027 --> 00:20:11,924
在高压气体环境下将金属沉积物转移到玻璃上制成的。
through a highly charged gas, a process known as sputter coating.

290
00:20:11,924 --> 00:20:19,375
这种工艺在大规模生产时效率尚可，但玻璃略带透明感，反射率最多只有40%左右。
It's effective to produce at scale, but slightly translucent and at best only reflects around 40% of light.

291
00:20:19,375 --> 00:20:22,400
换句话说，它永远不可能达到这个效果。
In other words, it'll never be as good as this.

292
00:20:25,200 --> 00:20:26,582
这是马里亚（Mariah）。
This is Mariah.

293
00:20:26,582 --> 00:20:33,680
这是一座建于2019年的非凡建筑，被认为是THE LINE的重要灵感来源之一。
It's a remarkable building that was constructed in 2019 and is thought to have been a key inspiration for the line.

294
00:20:34,799 --> 00:20:41,107
起初，它以抛光金属板包覆外墙，但这些金属板很快就在恶劣的风沙环境中受损变质。
At first, it was clad in polished metal sheets, but these quickly spoiled in the harsh sandy environment.

295
00:20:41,107 --> 00:20:44,791
要实现完美的镜面效果，你需要的是真正的镜子。
For a perfect mirror finish, you need a mirror.

296
00:20:44,791 --> 00:20:46,399
但镜子很脆弱。
But mirrors are fragile.

297
00:20:46,400 --> 00:20:50,886
在沙漠极端高温下，将镜面层压在一起的胶合层可能失效，
In the extreme heat of the desert, the lamination that binds them can fail,

298
00:20:50,886 --> 00:20:54,116
镀银涂层也可能从基底上剥落。
and the silver coating can peel away from its backing.

299
00:20:54,115 --> 00:20:59,823
为了生产出能够经受这些恶劣条件的产品，一种全新类型的镜子被研发出来。
To produce something that could withstand those conditions, an entirely new type of mirror was developed.

300
00:20:59,823 --> 00:21:02,943
通常，镜子由普通玻璃制成。
Normally, you'd make a mirror from standard glass.

301
00:21:02,944 --> 00:21:07,259
先生产大块玻璃板，裁切至所需尺寸，再涂上银质镜面层。
Large sheets are produced, cut to size, and then coated with a silver finish.

302
00:21:07,259 --> 00:21:12,400
但为了承受极端温度，玻璃还必须经过热处理，即钢化（tempered）。
But to survive the extreme temperatures, this glass would also have to be heat treated or tempered.

303
00:21:12,400 --> 00:21:15,360
而镜面涂层只能在钢化之后才能施加。
The mirror coating could only be applied after tempering.

304
00:21:15,360 --> 00:21:17,583
但钢化玻璃（tempered glass）无法再切割。
But tempered glass can't be cut.

305
00:21:17,583 --> 00:21:22,488
因此，为了生产马里亚所用的镜子，整条生产线不得不倒过来走。
So to produce the mirrors from Mariah, the entire production line had to be reversed.

306
00:21:22,488 --> 00:21:26,440
原始玻璃先被送去精确裁切至最终尺寸，
The raw glass was first sent to be precisely cut to its final size

307
00:21:26,440 --> 00:21:27,937
然后进行热处理，
and was then heat treated

308
00:21:27,937 --> 00:21:32,248
最后再送回最初的工厂进行新的镜面涂层工艺。
before being returned to its initial factory for the new mirror coating.

309
00:21:32,248 --> 00:21:38,678
除了银质喷镀，镜子还被涂覆了一层铜，以抵御强烈的太阳辐射。
Along with a silver spray, the mirrors were coated with copper to provide resistance against intense solar radiation.

310
00:21:38,677 --> 00:21:43,077
最终成果就是你今天所见的效果——反射率超过90%、
The result is what you see today, a surface with over 90% reflection

311
00:21:43,077 --> 00:21:46,959
能够承受地球上最严酷环境的镜面。
that can withstand some of the harshest conditions on Earth.

312
00:21:50,240 --> 00:21:53,848
说到地球上最严酷的环境，这里还有一个大问题。
Talking of the harshest conditions on Earth, here's a big one.

313
00:21:53,848 --> 00:21:56,804
THE LINE将不会进行户外空调（air conditioned）。
The line will not be airond conditioned.

314
00:21:56,804 --> 00:22:04,205
没错。THE LINE首席开发官在今年早些时候的一次演讲中证实，室外将不设空调。
That's right. The lack of outdoor cooling was confirmed in a presentation by the line's chief development officer earlier this year.

315
00:22:04,205 --> 00:22:08,192
要记住，这不是一栋建筑，而是一座城市。
You've got to remember that this isn't a building, it's a city.

316
00:22:08,193 --> 00:22:12,586
所以，在你的家里、办公室里或者任何室内空间，你可以开足空调。
So, inside your home or your office or wherever, you can have as much air con as you want.

317
00:22:12,586 --> 00:22:17,388
但在街道上，你就暴露在沙漠的自然气温之下。
But out on the streets, you're subject to the ambient temperature of the desert.

318
00:22:17,388 --> 00:22:22,410
如果这还不够糟糕，热岛效应（heat island effect）可能会让情况雪上加霜——
And if that's not bad enough, it could be made worse by the heat island effect,

319
00:22:22,410 --> 00:22:28,067
这是一种城市吸收和积聚热量的程度远超农村地区的现象。
a phenomenon where cities absorb and retain heat much more dramatically than rural areas.

320
00:22:28,067 --> 00:22:35,709
比如，在炎热天气里，伦敦市区可能比周边乡村高出多达5摄氏度，就是因为大量吸热的混凝土建筑。
In hot weather, for example, London can be up to 5° warmer than the surrounding countryside because of all its heat absorbing concrete.

321
00:22:35,709 --> 00:22:40,486
而在THE LINE里，会有大量的混凝土、钢铁和玻璃。
And in the line, there's going to be a lot of concrete and steel and glass.

322
00:22:40,486 --> 00:22:45,059
这是相当严重的问题，但目前我们能依赖的，只是一句保证，
Now, that's pretty major, but currently all we have to go on is an assurance

323
00:22:45,059 --> 00:22:47,947
说这一切都已经过充分考量和建模，
that this has all been thought about and modeled

324
00:22:47,947 --> 00:22:50,053
一切都会没问题。
and that it's all going to be okay.

325
00:22:50,053 --> 00:22:53,118
其中一个论点是，THE LINE墙壁的镜面外观
One argument made is that the mirror finish of the lines walls

326
00:22:53,118 --> 00:22:54,749
将反射大量光线，
is going to reflect so much light

327
00:22:54,750 --> 00:22:57,271
使得城市本身吸收的热量并不会太多。
that the city won't actually absorb that much heat.

328
00:22:57,271 --> 00:23:01,333
我们还被告知，玻璃将具有透气性，以允许空气流通。
We're also told the glass is going to be breathable to allow air to pass through.

329
00:23:01,333 --> 00:23:07,561
至于这究竟意味着巨大的墙壁上会设有通风口，还是正在发明一种全新材料，我们目前无从知晓。
Now, whether that means the vast walls will have vents in them or there's a brand new material being invented, we just don't know.

330
00:23:07,561 --> 00:23:10,320
但这并不能让人感到乐观。
But it doesn't exactly fill you with optimism.

331
00:23:14,480 --> 00:23:16,165
看来，THE LINE里的生活将主要在各个模块中展开。
So, it looks like Life in the Line

332
00:23:16,165 --> 00:23:18,345
看来，THE LINE里的生活将主要在各个模块中展开。
is going to be largely lived within modules.

333
00:23:18,345 --> 00:23:22,816
每个模块都被设计为包含你所需的全部基本设施，步行即可抵达。
Each one is being designed to contain all the basic amenities that you need,

334
00:23:22,816 --> 00:23:24,640
每个模块都被设计为包含你所需的全部基本设施，步行即可抵达。
accessible within a short walk.

335
00:23:24,640 --> 00:23:28,334
本质上，这是哥本哈根、苏黎世等城市推行的15分钟城市（15-minute city）概念的延伸。
Essentially, it's an extension of the 15-minute city concept

336
00:23:28,334 --> 00:23:31,350
本质上，这是哥本哈根、苏黎世等城市推行的15分钟城市（15-minute city）概念的延伸。
that you see in places like Copenhagen or Zurich.

337
00:23:31,350 --> 00:23:33,090
但要实现这一点，
But for that to be possible,

338
00:23:33,090 --> 00:23:36,321
你必须能在不被烈日烤化的情况下四处走动。
you've got to be able to get around without melting.

339
00:23:37,120 --> 00:23:40,320
如果你需要去更远的地方，就得依靠某种交通方式。
And if you need to go any further, you'll need some form of transportation.

340
00:23:40,480 --> 00:23:43,800
但在探讨交通如何运作之前，
But before we can get stuck into how transport will work,

341
00:23:43,800 --> 00:23:46,246
我们先来解释一下为什么这座城市是一条线。
we need to explain why the line is a line.

342
00:23:46,246 --> 00:23:49,760
所以，看来我们建城市的方式一直都是错的。
So apparently we've all been doing our cities wrong.

343
00:23:49,760 --> 00:23:53,019
这是伦敦，约有860万人口，
This is London, home to about 8.6 million people,

344
00:23:53,019 --> 00:23:55,148
略低于THE LINE全面建成后
just shy of the 9 million people

345
00:23:55,148 --> 00:23:58,740
最终能容纳的900万人。
that could ultimately live in the fully realized line.

346
00:23:58,820 --> 00:24:02,240
它吞噬了英格兰东南部相当大的一块土地。
It swallows up a sizable chunk of the southeast of England.

347
00:24:02,240 --> 00:24:05,520
现在再来看看与THE LINE的对比。
Now look what happens if we compare that to the line.

348
00:24:05,600 --> 00:24:09,552
他们想表达的观点是：这代表着城市建设的旧模式。
The point they're making is that this represents the old way of building cities.

349
00:24:09,552 --> 00:24:11,693
它没有经过任何真正的规划，就这样蔓延生长。
It's grown without any real plan.

350
00:24:11,693 --> 00:24:14,344
它无序扩张，效率低下。
It's sprawling and it's inefficient.

351
00:24:14,344 --> 00:24:17,746
如果我们能把这些人都安置在这座时尚、技术先进的建筑里，
Wouldn't it be much neater if we could take all those people

352
00:24:17,746 --> 00:24:21,432
岂不是好得多？
and house them in this slick, technologically advanced structure?

353
00:24:21,432 --> 00:24:21,489
岂不是好得多？


354
00:24:21,489 --> 00:24:25,810
而要做到这一点，有一样东西必须被彻底淘汰——汽车。
And to do that, there's one key thing you need to get rid of.

355
00:24:25,810 --> 00:24:26,164
而要做到这一点，有一样东西必须被彻底淘汰——汽车。
Cars.

356
00:24:26,164 --> 00:24:29,995
汽车或许是沙特阿拉伯富裕的重要原因，
Now, cars may be a large part of why Saudi Arabia is rich,

357
00:24:29,995 --> 00:24:32,240
但这里着眼的是未来。
but this is looking to the future.

358
00:24:32,240 --> 00:24:34,960
汽车占用大量空间，还会发生碰撞事故。
Cars take up a lot of space. They crash.

359
00:24:34,960 --> 00:24:36,070
它们必须停放。
They've got to be parked.

360
00:24:36,070 --> 00:24:37,617
它们载不了多少人。
They don't carry many people.

361
00:24:37,618 --> 00:24:41,570
THE LINE承诺的是更好的替代方案。
What the line's promising is something much better.

362
00:24:41,570 --> 00:24:44,544
在最底层，你将看到THE LINE的高速铁路（high-speed railway）。
Here at the bottom, you'll find the lines highspeed railway.

363
00:24:44,543 --> 00:24:48,101
它将连接国际机场与西端。
It's going to connect the international airport to the western tip.

364
00:24:48,101 --> 00:24:51,784
据说全程只需20分钟，
Supposedly, it's going to take 20 minutes to make that whole journey,

365
00:24:51,784 --> 00:24:54,720
这将比当今世界上任何一列火车都要快。
which will be faster than any train in existence today.

366
00:24:54,720 --> 00:24:59,674
在此之上，THE LINE的大众公共交通（mass transit）系统——一套市郊风格的轨道系统——
Above all this, the line's general mass transit, a suburban style rail system,

367
00:24:59,674 --> 00:25:01,579
每隔1.5公里设一站。
will be stopping every 1.5 km.

368
00:25:01,579 --> 00:25:05,871
然后，分布在THE LINE五个主层（primary decks）之间的是一张轻轨（light rail）网络，
Then distributed between the lines five primary decks

369
00:25:05,871 --> 00:25:09,920
每隔100米停靠一次。
will be a light rail network stopping every 100 m.

370
00:25:10,159 --> 00:25:13,952
连接各层之间的是一系列自动扶梯和电梯。
Connecting people between the levels will be a series of escalators and lifts.

371
00:25:13,952 --> 00:25:18,119
这理应是THE LINE的一大卖点——
Now this is supposed to be one of the big selling points of the line

372
00:25:18,119 --> 00:25:21,919
它的形态本身就是一种更好、更高效的城市理念。
that its shape is a better, more efficient concept for a city.

373
00:25:21,919 --> 00:25:23,904
但事实真的如此吗？
But is that really the case?

374
00:25:23,904 --> 00:25:27,012
要回答这个问题，来看看这个。
Well, to answer that, take a look at this.

375
00:25:27,013 --> 00:25:31,198
这是苹果园区（Apple Park），史蒂夫·乔布斯最后的伟大创作。
This is Apple Park, Steve Jobs's last great creation.

376
00:25:31,197 --> 00:25:32,474
它与THE LINE有相似之处——
It's similar to the line

377
00:25:32,474 --> 00:25:35,667
同样拥有一个容纳万物的简洁结构。
in that it has this simple structure that houses everything.

378
00:25:35,667 --> 00:25:35,720
同样拥有一个容纳万物的简洁结构。


379
00:25:35,720 --> 00:25:38,640
但不同的是，它是一个圆形。
But it's different because it's a circle.

380
00:25:39,039 --> 00:25:42,761
这是刻意为之，因为圆形承载着某种理念。
That was deliberate because a circle embodies certain ideas.

381
00:25:42,761 --> 00:25:45,463
首先，在圆形中没有等级之分，
For one, in a circle, there's no hierarchy,

382
00:25:45,463 --> 00:25:48,228
没有高低之别，没有人人觊觎的转角办公室，
no top or bottom, no coveted corner offices,

383
00:25:48,228 --> 00:25:51,118
内部空间被所有人平等共享。
and the space inside is equally shared by all.

384
00:25:51,118 --> 00:25:54,000
它在通行方面同样出色，说来也不是什么双关——
It's also good for getting around, no pun intended.

385
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:55,603
任何人需要走的最长路径，
The furthest anyone has to travel

